Benjamin Francis Ford (May 12, 1901 – June 20, 1986), known professionally as The Duke of Paducah, was an American country comedian, radio host and banjo player popular from the 1940s to the 1960s.
He enlisted in the U.S. Navy in 1918.
After his discharge in 1922, he joined McGinty's Oklahoma Cowboy Band, a Dixieland jazz group, as a banjo player.
In 1929, Ford made his debut on WLS-AM in Chicago, Illinois.
In the early 1930s, while working at KWK in St. Louis, Ford took the stage name The Duke of Paducah.
In 1937, he founded the Renfro Valley Barn Dance with Red Foley and John Lair.
From 1942–1959, Ford was a regular on the Grand Ole Opry where he became a member.
In 1958, he began hosting an early morning television show, Country Junction, on WLAC-TV in Nashville, which he hosted for several years, being succeeded by disc jockey Eddie Hill.
